1
00:00:05,508 --> 00:00:07,628
Let’s start with the market structure. 

2
00:00:07,628 --> 00:00:11,308
Market structure is the 
backbone of technical analysis. 

3
00:00:11,308 --> 00:00:17,268
It's about figuring out who's in control 
– demand or supply, buyers or sellers. 

4
00:00:17,268 --> 00:00:21,788
When demand and supply influence 
price movement, trends are born. 
  

5
00:00:21,788 --> 00:00:28,828
An uptrend, or a bullish trend, is characterized 
by higher swing highs and higher swing lows. This  

6
00:00:28,828 --> 00:00:35,068
trend remains intact until a lower low emerges.
A downtrend, or a bearish trend,  

7
00:00:35,068 --> 00:00:41,388
shows lower lows and lower highs, and it 
continues until a higher high appears. 

8
00:00:41,388 --> 00:00:47,708
Markets don't always trend; they can transition 
into consolidation phases or a sideways trend. 

9
00:00:47,708 --> 00:00:54,108
A sideways trend displays roughly equal highs 
and lows, with price consolidating in a range.
  

10
00:00:54,108 --> 00:01:01,308
To identify the shift from trend to consolidation, 
watch for failed tests of recent highs and lows. 
  

11
00:01:01,308 --> 00:01:07,228
To confirm a healthy trend, look for price 
to break and close above or below previous  

12
00:01:07,228 --> 00:01:13,148
highs or lows. Multiple closes beyond 
these levels indicate strong momentum. 
  

13
00:01:13,148 --> 00:01:18,828
A failure to hold above or below 
suggests a potential false breakout. 

14
00:01:18,828 --> 00:01:22,788
Lastly, keep an eye out for the 
breaks in market structure. 
  

15
00:01:22,788 --> 00:01:28,708
In an uptrend, a break in the market structure 
occurs when price makes a new lower low,  

16
00:01:28,708 --> 00:01:33,708
and a new lower high, indicating 
potential weakness or reversal. 

17
00:01:33,708 --> 00:01:40,068
Similarly, in a downtrend, a break of structure 
happens when price forms a new higher high,  

18
00:01:40,068 --> 00:01:44,028
and a new higher low, serving as a warning sign.
 
Market cycles 

19
00:01:44,028 --> 00:01:47,948
All markets move in cycles, 
which are: Accumulation,  

20
00:01:47,948 --> 00:01:51,309
Mark Up, Distribution, and Mark Down.
Each cycle tells a unique story about  

21
00:01:51,309 --> 00:01:53,228
the battle between supply and demand.
 
Accumulation is when the price has  

22
00:01:53,228 --> 00:01:58,468
fallen to a point where the price may 
seem stuck in a range. In this phase,  

23
00:01:58,468 --> 00:02:03,788
buyers are quietly gaining strength.
 
In the Mark Up phase, the buyers finally  

24
00:02:03,788 --> 00:02:07,748
break free from the range and 
start pushing prices higher,  

25
00:02:07,748 --> 00:02:13,028
confirming that the buyers are in control.
 
In the Distribution phase, after the previous  

26
00:02:13,028 --> 00:02:18,268
significant price increase, sellers start 
to regain control, and the price action  

27
00:02:18,268 --> 00:02:24,268
flattens out once again. Lower tops and 
flat bottoms characterize this range,  

28
00:02:24,268 --> 00:02:29,588
as the sellers prepare to take over.
 
Finally, the Markdown Phase arrives,  

29
00:02:29,588 --> 00:02:34,868
and the sellers steer prices below the 
lower level of the distribution phase,  

30
00:02:34,868 --> 00:02:40,588
and a strong downtrend emerges.
 
If you can spot the end of the Accumulation stage,  

31
00:02:40,588 --> 00:02:46,388
be ready to buy at the beginning of the 
Mark Up, riding the wave of rising prices. 

32
00:02:46,388 --> 00:02:52,268
Similarly, if you can identify the end of the 
Distribution phase, be ready to sell and profit  

33
00:02:52,268 --> 00:02:55,148
from the Markdown's downward momentum.
 
Support/resistance 

34
00:02:55,148 --> 00:03:00,028
Mastering support and resistance is 
very important in technical analysis. 

35
00:03:00,028 --> 00:03:04,668
Support acts as the floor beneath 
the market, an area where the price  

36
00:03:04,668 --> 00:03:09,908
has shown a tendency to stop falling.
Buyers might see value at this level  

37
00:03:09,908 --> 00:03:15,948
and start buying, creating a demand zone that 
prevents the price from dropping further. 
  

38
00:03:15,948 --> 00:03:20,708
Resistance acts like a ceiling above the 
market, an area where the price has shown a  

39
00:03:20,708 --> 00:03:27,268
tendency to stop rising. It's like an invisible 
barrier that keeps prices from moving too high. 

40
00:03:27,268 --> 00:03:31,148
Sellers might see it as a fair 
price to sell their positions,  

41
00:03:31,148 --> 00:03:34,548
creating a supply zone.
 
This is how you spot these  

42
00:03:34,548 --> 00:03:39,188
levels. You need to follow some simple rules.
First, look for the extreme swing highs and lows,  

43
00:03:39,188 --> 00:03:43,268
the highest and lowest points 
the price has reached recently.
  

44
00:03:43,268 --> 00:03:46,948
Also, look for at least 
two rejections of an area.
  

45
00:03:46,948 --> 00:03:52,148
The level should be obvious, jumping right 
out at you when you glance at the chart.
  

46
00:03:52,148 --> 00:03:56,068
Also, the move away from the 
area should be significant.
  

47
00:03:56,068 --> 00:04:01,108
Another condition: the level should have 
acted as both support and resistance,  

48
00:04:01,108 --> 00:04:04,828
respected from both sides.
 
And finally, the level should  

49
00:04:04,828 --> 00:04:09,828
have been recently respected or formed.
You don't need all these conditions  

50
00:04:09,828 --> 00:04:14,428
to draw a level, but the more 
rules it fulfills, the better.
  

51
00:04:14,428 --> 00:04:20,068
Now, very important, the more times a 
level is tested, the weaker it becomes.  

52
00:04:20,068 --> 00:04:25,628
Really strong support and resistance levels 
immediately push the price away from them. 

53
00:04:25,628 --> 00:04:31,388
If the price can hang around or quickly revisit 
the level, it suggests a lack of conviction  

54
00:04:31,388 --> 00:04:37,708
from buyers or sellers. Multiple tests of 
a level can set the stage for a breakout.
  

55
00:04:37,708 --> 00:04:43,108
And another tip: when drawing support and 
resistance, focus on the significant levels  

56
00:04:43,628 --> 00:04:47,788
rather than cluttering your 
chart with every possible level. 

57
00:04:47,788 --> 00:04:54,028
And very important, treat these levels as zones 
rather than exact lines, as the price might break  

58
00:04:54,028 --> 00:04:57,308
your line or turn before touching it.
 
Candlesticks 

59
00:04:57,308 --> 00:05:02,788
Candlesticks give you a visual representation 
of the battle between buyers and sellers. 

60
00:05:02,788 --> 00:05:09,388
Each candlestick reveals the open, high, low, 
and close price for a specific time period,  

61
00:05:09,388 --> 00:05:14,588
whether it's a minute, an hour, or a day.
 
The candle body represents the distance  

62
00:05:14,588 --> 00:05:19,148
between the opening and closing 
price, while the high and low show  

63
00:05:19,148 --> 00:05:24,828
the extremes reached during that time period.
The length of the candlestick body and the  

64
00:05:24,828 --> 00:05:28,268
wicks are very important in technical analysis, 
for revealing the buying and selling pressure. 
  

65
00:05:28,268 --> 00:05:33,068
A long upper wick suggests strong 
selling pressure, as sellers drove  

66
00:05:33,068 --> 00:05:37,868
the price down from the high. 
 
A long lower wick indicates strong  

67
00:05:37,868 --> 00:05:42,668
buying pressure, with buyers pushing 
the price back up from the low. 
  

68
00:05:42,668 --> 00:05:47,028
Short wicks imply minimal 
buying or selling pressure.
  

69
00:05:47,028 --> 00:05:51,108
A long body indicates strong 
buying or selling pressure,  

70
00:05:51,108 --> 00:05:55,228
while a short body suggests 
less intense activity. 
  

71
00:05:55,228 --> 00:06:00,508
Sometimes, you might see candlesticks 
with no wicks at all, just long bodies. 

72
00:06:00,508 --> 00:06:06,428
These are momentum candles, emphasizing 
the market sentiment even more strongly.
  

73
00:06:06,428 --> 00:06:11,668
Also, pay close attention to engulfing 
bars (which appear when a larger candle  

74
00:06:11,668 --> 00:06:17,748
engulfing a smaller one) and to pin bars, 
with their long tails and small bodies. 
  

75
00:06:17,748 --> 00:06:23,068
Also look for inside bars (when one or more 
candlesticks that are completely contained  

76
00:06:23,068 --> 00:06:27,708
within the range of a larger candle) 
 
The real magic happens when you combine  

77
00:06:27,708 --> 00:06:33,388
these candlestick patterns with the right 
context, and you analyze a series of candle  

78
00:06:33,388 --> 00:06:38,028
within the broader price trend. 
 
So observe how candles form in  

79
00:06:38,028 --> 00:06:43,188
relation to previous bars, and look 
for engulfing candles, inside bars,  

80
00:06:43,188 --> 00:06:50,414
and pin bars at major levels of support and 
resistance, or during significant trend phases.
  

81
00:06:50,414 --> 00:06:52,188
Price patterns
A group or series of  

82
00:06:52,188 --> 00:06:56,628
candlesticks form price patterns.
In technical analysis we can have  

83
00:06:56,628 --> 00:07:01,988
reversal patterns, which indicate that the 
price might be about to change direction,  

84
00:07:01,988 --> 00:07:08,188
or continuation patterns, which signal the price 
will likely keep moving in its current direction.
  

85
00:07:08,188 --> 00:07:13,388
Double tops and bottoms are the most 
important reversal patterns worth watching. 

86
00:07:13,388 --> 00:07:19,268
A double top happens when the price fails to make 
a higher high and instead matches the previous  

87
00:07:19,268 --> 00:07:25,148
high, hinting at a potential bearish reversal. 
 
A double bottom is the opposite – the price  

88
00:07:25,148 --> 00:07:30,028
fails to make a lower low and matches 
the previous low, suggesting a bullish  

89
00:07:30,028 --> 00:07:34,948
reversal could be on the horizon.
 
Continuation patterns appear as  

90
00:07:34,948 --> 00:07:41,068
consolidations after a period of trending.
Ascending and descending triangles have a  

91
00:07:41,068 --> 00:07:46,188
clear directional bias, with buyers 
or sellers showing their strength. 
  

92
00:07:46,188 --> 00:07:50,828
Flags and wedges slope in the opposite 
direction of the prevailing trend,  

93
00:07:50,828 --> 00:07:55,708
hinting at a potential continuation. 
 
Rectangles form when the price  

94
00:07:55,708 --> 00:08:01,388
consolidates sideways, bounded by 
clear support and resistance levels.
 
 
  

95
00:08:01,388 --> 00:08:06,348
Very important: location and context 
of these patterns are crucial. A  

96
00:08:06,348 --> 00:08:11,468
continuation pattern is only useful if 
there's an existing trend to continue,  

97
00:08:11,468 --> 00:08:17,988
and a reversal pattern needs a trend to reverse. 
 
Also, be aware that we can sometimes see what  

98
00:08:17,988 --> 00:08:24,028
we want to see, so it's important to stay 
objective and don’t rely too much on patterns.
  

99
00:08:24,028 --> 00:08:30,748
No pattern is foolproof, and they will fail a lot. 
It's often easier to spot them after the fact.  

100
00:08:30,748 --> 00:08:37,708
Textbook patterns are rare in real life, so be 
prepared for price spikes and fake breakouts. 
 
  

101
00:08:37,708 --> 00:08:39,428
Fibonacci
Fibonacci retracements are one  

102
00:08:39,428 --> 00:08:45,788
of the most popular tools in technical analysis 
and they work best when the market is trending. 
  

103
00:08:45,788 --> 00:08:49,548
The theory behind this is 
that after a trend begins,  

104
00:08:49,548 --> 00:08:55,908
the price will often retrace to a previous level 
before continuing in the direction of the trend.
 
  

105
00:08:55,908 --> 00:08:59,708
To find these Fibonacci levels, 
you need to identify recent  

106
00:08:59,708 --> 00:09:05,028
significant Swing Highs and Swing Lows.
Then, you use the Fibonacci tool to connect  

107
00:09:05,028 --> 00:09:12,948
the Swing High to the Swing Low in a downtrend, 
or the Swing Low to the Swing High in an uptrend. 

108
00:09:12,948 --> 00:09:19,348
The idea is to buy when the price retraces to 
a Fibonacci support level during an uptrend,  

109
00:09:19,348 --> 00:09:25,348
and to sell when the price retraces to a 
Fibonacci resistance level during a downtrend. 
 
  

110
00:09:25,348 --> 00:09:29,888
Choosing the correct price swing is crucial 
when using Fibonacci retracements. 
  

111
00:09:29,888 --> 00:09:36,588
So focus on larger time frames and avoid using 
the tool on very small price moves, as the levels  

112
00:09:36,588 --> 00:09:42,028
will be too close together to be reliable.
The best Fibonacci retracements are those  

113
00:09:42,028 --> 00:09:46,845
that are easy to spot on a chart 
without having to look too hard.
  

114
00:09:46,845 --> 00:09:48,708
Supply and demand zones
Now let’s talk about supply and demand  

115
00:09:48,708 --> 00:09:55,388
zones. These areas are formed when big market 
players are placing large quantities of orders.
  

116
00:09:55,388 --> 00:10:02,068
A demand zone is where buyers are likely to step 
in and start buying, causing the price to go up. 

117
00:10:02,068 --> 00:10:06,948
A supply zone is where sellers are 
likely to step in and start selling,  

118
00:10:06,948 --> 00:10:10,988
causing the price to go down.
In theory, if price returns to  

119
00:10:10,988 --> 00:10:16,988
certain supply and demand zones, it has a 
high probability of rejecting these areas.
  

120
00:10:16,988 --> 00:10:20,788
This is how to mark supply and 
demand zones on your charts. 

121
00:10:20,788 --> 00:10:25,108
First things first, you'll need 
to identify the overall trend. 

122
00:10:25,108 --> 00:10:30,388
Next, look for significant turning points 
in the price action. These are the points  

123
00:10:30,388 --> 00:10:36,228
where the price made a sharp reversal, 
either from a low point or a high point.
  

124
00:10:36,228 --> 00:10:42,388
To mark a demand zone, find a low point in the 
market where the price bounced up strongly. 

125
00:10:42,988 --> 00:10:46,548
Locate the last bearish 
candle before the price move. 

126
00:10:46,548 --> 00:10:52,908
Then draw a horizontal line at the low point of 
the candle, and another one at the high point of  

127
00:10:52,908 --> 00:10:59,508
the candlestick. This is your demand zone.
 
To mark a supply zone, you find a high point  

128
00:10:59,508 --> 00:11:03,548
where the price fell sharply.
Locate the last bullish  

129
00:11:03,548 --> 00:11:08,268
candle before the price move.
Draw a horizontal line at the  

130
00:11:08,268 --> 00:11:15,428
high point and another one at the low point of 
the candlestick. And this is your supply zone.
  

131
00:11:15,428 --> 00:11:20,428
When marking zones, focus on the 
most recent and significant zones.  

132
00:11:20,428 --> 00:11:27,028
Older zones may not be as relevant anymore.
And adjust your zones as needed. If the price  

133
00:11:27,028 --> 00:11:31,708
breaks through a zone decisively, 
it may no longer be valid.
 
  

134
00:11:31,708 --> 00:11:33,228
Volume
Volume is very important  

135
00:11:33,228 --> 00:11:39,908
in technical analysis. It basically tells you how 
much trading activity there is in a given period.
  

136
00:11:39,908 --> 00:11:45,548
When volume is high, it means there are a lot 
of market participants involved in the move,  

137
00:11:45,548 --> 00:11:50,108
including the "smart money" (the big 
players who bring the most turnover). 

138
00:11:50,108 --> 00:11:56,348
This is a good sign because it confirms that the 
market activity is real and not just a fluke. 
  

139
00:11:56,348 --> 00:12:01,868
On the other hand, low volume suggests that 
there aren't many traders interested in the  

140
00:12:01,868 --> 00:12:06,708
current price levels, which could mean 
that the trend is running out of steam.
  

141
00:12:06,708 --> 00:12:12,908
Volume can also help you evaluate the health of 
a trend. In an uptrend, you want to see volume  

142
00:12:12,908 --> 00:12:19,108
increasing as the price moves higher, and you 
want to see it decreasing during pullbacks. 
  

143
00:12:19,108 --> 00:12:23,668
If volume is decreasing while prices 
are rising, it's a warning sign that  

144
00:12:23,668 --> 00:12:28,988
the uptrend might be losing momentum. 
 
Another important thing to watch for is  

145
00:12:28,988 --> 00:12:34,068
volume spikes at certain price levels.
Look for periods when volume suddenly  

146
00:12:34,068 --> 00:12:39,828
jumps up. It means that a lot of traders are 
interested in that particular price. If the  

147
00:12:39,828 --> 00:12:46,388
spike is really big (like, bigger than any other 
recent spikes), it's called a volume climax.
  

148
00:12:46,388 --> 00:12:52,188
Volume can also help you validate breakouts. 
When a market is consolidating and trading  

149
00:12:52,188 --> 00:12:58,628
sideways on low volume, a sudden increase in 
volume could mean that a breakout is coming. 

150
00:12:58,628 --> 00:13:04,508
If the breakout happens with rising volume, 
that's a good sign that the breakout it's legit. 

151
00:13:04,508 --> 00:13:09,828
But if the breakout happens on low 
volume, it might be a fake-out.
  

152
00:13:09,828 --> 00:13:11,308
Elliott Wave Theory
Elliott Wave Theory is  

153
00:13:11,308 --> 00:13:17,068
all about identifying repeating movements 
on price charts, which are called waves. 

154
00:13:17,068 --> 00:13:19,588
These waves can be either impulsive 
(moving with the trend) or  

155
00:13:19,588 --> 00:13:22,508
corrective (moving against the trend).
 
Impulsive waves represent the  

156
00:13:22,508 --> 00:13:27,668
direction of the current trend.
Corrective waves work against the prevailing trend  

157
00:13:27,668 --> 00:13:33,788
and are usually weaker and less aggressive. 
 
An uptrend typically has three large upward  

158
00:13:33,788 --> 00:13:39,428
price impulses and two corrections, 
creating a five-wave pattern. 

159
00:13:39,428 --> 00:13:44,988
This uptrend is then followed by three waves 
lower: an impulse down, a correction to the  

160
00:13:44,988 --> 00:13:48,948
upside, and another impulse down. 
 
There are three golden  

161
00:13:48,948 --> 00:13:55,188
rules in Elliott Wave Theory:
Wave 2 cannot go past the start of wave 1. 

162
00:13:55,188 --> 00:14:02,988
Wave 3 cannot be the shortest wave (so wave 
1 or wave 5, or both, must be shorter). 

163
00:14:02,988 --> 00:14:08,188
And Wave 4 cannot go into the 
price territory of wave 2 (so  

164
00:14:08,188 --> 00:14:15,188
waves 2 and 4 must have clear price separation).
 
It's best to trade in the direction of the impulse  

165
00:14:15,188 --> 00:14:22,028
waves, as they represent the largest price moves.
So in an uptrend, buy during pullbacks or at  

166
00:14:22,028 --> 00:14:26,828
the end of a corrective wave, and 
ride the next impulse wave higher. 

167
00:14:26,828 --> 00:14:33,088
In a downtrend, sell at the end of a corrective 
wave to profit from the next impulse wave down.
  

168
00:14:33,088 --> 00:14:35,988
Gaps
Now let's talk about market gaps. 

169
00:14:35,988 --> 00:14:41,828
A gap happens when the price jumps higher or 
lower from the previous price, leaving an empty  

170
00:14:41,828 --> 00:14:45,268
space between the two prices.
Gaps happen because of an  

171
00:14:45,268 --> 00:14:50,708
imbalance between supply and demand.
 
An up gap forms when a candle’s low price  

172
00:14:50,708 --> 00:14:57,108
is higher than the previous candle’s high price.
A down gap is the opposite – the high price is  

173
00:14:57,108 --> 00:15:02,188
lower than the previous low price.
Gaps show that something significant  

174
00:15:02,188 --> 00:15:07,548
has changed in the fundamentals or the 
psychology of the market participants. 
  

175
00:15:07,548 --> 00:15:12,468
There are four main types of gaps:
First we have common gaps: These gaps are  

176
00:15:12,468 --> 00:15:18,228
normal, small, and happen fairly often. They 
usually get filled quickly and don't provide  

177
00:15:18,228 --> 00:15:24,868
much insight. A gap fill is when the price 
action retraces to the level before the gap.
  

178
00:15:24,868 --> 00:15:30,668
Breakaway gaps occur when the price breaks 
out of a trading range or congestion area.  

179
00:15:30,668 --> 00:15:36,748
They need market enthusiasm and a significant 
increase in volume to happen. If the volume  

180
00:15:36,748 --> 00:15:42,868
increases when the gap occurs, it means the 
new trend has a good chance of continuing. 
  

181
00:15:42,868 --> 00:15:49,148
Runaway gaps happen in the middle of a strong 
trend and show that the trend is accelerating.  

182
00:15:49,148 --> 00:15:54,668
They're a sign of increased enthusiasm 
and usually happen with high volume. 
  

183
00:15:54,668 --> 00:15:59,548
Exhaustion gaps occur near the end of a 
strong trend and they're often followed by  

184
00:15:59,548 --> 00:16:05,468
a sharp reversal in the opposite direction. 
Exhaustion gaps are usually filled quickly,  

185
00:16:05,468 --> 00:16:08,188
signaling the end of the trend.
 
Trading indicators 

186
00:16:08,188 --> 00:16:12,508
Technical analysis relies heavily 
on "trading indicators" to show  

187
00:16:12,508 --> 00:16:17,148
various aspects of price activity.
These indicators can be divided into  

188
00:16:17,148 --> 00:16:23,108
four main categories: trend-following, 
momentum, volume, and volatility.
  

189
00:16:23,108 --> 00:16:29,308
Trend indicators, like VWAP and moving averages, 
measure the strength and direction of a  

190
00:16:29,308 --> 00:16:35,228
trend. However, they have a main drawback – they 
lag the price and give trading signals after a  

191
00:16:35,228 --> 00:16:41,708
trend has already been established, causing you to 
potentially miss the initial move of a new trend.
  

192
00:16:41,708 --> 00:16:47,308
Momentum indicators, also known as oscillators, 
measure the relative strength of recent price  

193
00:16:47,308 --> 00:16:54,508
moves and plot a value between 0 and 100. 
They work well in ranging markets but can  

194
00:16:54,508 --> 00:16:59,028
lead to false signals when markets 
are trending. RSI, Stochastic, and  

